{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_01A7xkCv4GkhbXybN6ooUVex","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-3-7-sonnet-20250219","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SbhoPzytU7sKMLoJtVLczE","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/clsi/tmphcekju_a/fixed_minimum_spanning_tree.py","content":"def minimum_spanning_tree(weight_by_edge):
    group_by_node = {}
    mst_edges = set()

    for edge in sorted(weight_by_edge, key=weight_by_edge.__getitem__):
        u, v = edge
        if group_by_node.setdefault(u, {u}) != group_by_node.setdefault(v, {v}):
            mst_edges.add(edge)
            group_by_node[u].update(group_by_node[v])
            for node in group_by_node[v]:
                group_by_node[node] = group_by_node[u]

    return mst_edges




"""
Minimum Spanning Tree


Kruskal's algorithm implementation.

Input:
    weight_by_edge: A dict of the form {(u, v): weight} for every undirected graph edge {u, v}

Precondition:
    The input graph is connected

Output:
    A set of edges that connects all the vertices of the input graph and has the least possible total weight.

Example:
